maller than for df=15.\n\nFor example, at df=15.38, critical t for p=0.01 is about 2.937 as before, our t=2.914<2.937, so p>0.01.\n\nBut from interpolation, for df=15, p≈0.0116\n\nFor df=16, t=2.914, critical t for α=0.01 is 2.921, 2.914<2.921, so p>0.01.\n\nt=2.914 for df=16, p-value: df=16, t=2.921 for p=0.01, t=2.583 for p=0.02? I need values.\n\nGenerally, p-value is less than 0.05 but greater than 0.01.\n\nSince for α=0.05, we reject, it's significant.\n\nSo answer should be yes.\n\nBut let me see the data: Type 1 has values like 4.47, 4.45, low, while Type 2 has 7.71, 8.93, high, so visually different.\n\nBut statistically confirmed.\n\nSo I think there is a significant difference.\n</think>\nTo determine if there is a statistically significant difference in rubber production between Type 1 and Type 2 trees, an independent two-sample t-test (Welch's t-test) is used. This test is appropriate because the sample sizes are small (Type 1: \\(n_1 = 16\\), Type 2: \\(n_2 = 12\\)), the population variances are unknown and unequal (as confirmed by an F-test), and the samples are independent.\n\n### Hypotheses\n- Null hypothesis (\\(H_0\\)): \\(\\mu_1 = \\mu_2\\) (no difference in mean rubber production between the two types).\n- Alternative hypothesis (\\(H_1\\)): \\(\\mu_1 \\neq \\mu_2\\) (there is a difference in mean rubber production).\n\n### Data Summary\n- **Type 1 sample**: 6.21, 5.70, 6.04, 4.47, 5.22, 4.45, 4.84, 5.84, 5.88, 5.82, 6.09, 5.59, 6.06, 5.59, 6.74, 5.55  \n  - Sample mean (\\(\\bar{x}_1\\)): 5.6306 kg  \n  - Sample variance (\\(s_1^2\\)): 0.3880 kg²  \n  - Sample size (\\(n_1\\)): 16\n\n- **Type 2 sample**: 4.28, 7.71, 6.48, 7.71, 7.37, 7.20, 7.06, 6.40, 8.93, 5.91, 5.51, 6.36  \n  - Sample mean (\\(\\bar{x}_2\\)): 6.7433 kg  \n  - Sample variance (\\(s_2^2\\)): 1.4578 kg²  \n  - Sample size (\\(n_2\\)): 12\n\n### Test Statistic (Welch's t-test)\nThe test statistic is calculated as:\n\\[\nt = \\frac{\\bar{x}_1 - \\bar{x}_2}{\\sqrt{\\frac{s_1^2}{n_1} + \\frac{s_2^2}{n_2}}}\n\\]\nSubstituting the values:\n\\[\nt = \\frac{5.6306 - 6.7433}{\\sqrt{\\frac{0.3880}{16} + \\frac{1.4578}{12}}} = \\frac{-1.1127}{\\sqrt{0.02425 + 0.12149}} = \\frac{-1.1127}{\\sqrt{0.14574}} = \\frac{-1.1127}{0.38176} = -2.914\n\\]\nThe absolute value of the test statistic is \\(|t| = 2.914\\).\n\n### Degrees of Freedom\nThe degrees of freedom are approximated using the Welch-Satterthwaite equation:\n\\[\ndf = \\frac{\\left( \\frac{s_1^2}{n_1} + \\frac{s_2^2}{n_2} \\right)^2}{\\frac{(s_1^2 / n_1)^2}{n_1 - 1} + \\frac{(s_2^2 / n_2)^2}{n_2 - 1}}\n\\]\nSubstituting the values:\n\\[\ndf = \\frac{(0.14574)^2}{\\frac{(0.02425)^2}{15} + \\frac{(0.12149)^2}{11}} = \\frac{0.02124}{0.00003922 + 0.00134164} = \\frac{0.02124}{0.00138086} \\approx 15.38\n\\]\n\n### Critical Value and Decision\nFor a two-tailed test at a significance level of \\(\\alpha = 0.05\\) and \\(df \\approx 15.38\\), the critical t-value is approximately 2.127 (interpolated from t-distribution tables, using \\(df = 15\\): 2.131 and \\(df = 16\\): 2.120).  \n- Since \\(|t| = 2.914 > 2.127\\), the null hypothesis is rejected.\n\n### Conclusion\nThere is a statistically significant difference in the average rubber production between Type 1 and Type 2 trees at the 5% significance level. The mean production for Type 1 trees (5.6306 kg) is significantly lower than for Type 2 trees (6.7433 kg).\n\n### Additional Notes\n- **Variance Equality Check**: An F-test confirmed that the variances are unequal (\\(F = s_2^2 / s_1^2 = 1.4578 / 0.3880 = 3.756\\), \\(F_{0.025}(11, 15) \\approx 3.01\\), so \\(F > F_{\\text{critical}}\\)). Thus, Welch's t-test is appropriate.\n- **p-value Approximation**: The p-value is approximately 0.011 (based on interpolation for \\(df = 15\\)), which is less than 0.05, supporting the rejection of \\(H_0\\).\n- **Relevance of Retrieved Documents**: Document 2 (test statistic) and Document 3 (hypothesis test) are directly relevant to the statistical method used. The other documents are not directly applicable to this analysis.\n\n\\boxed{\\text{yes}}"
